Shrines, temples, castles, or statues of deities and Buddhas.
Some may feature obsolete materials or inherit structural flaws,
but would we ever call their restoration "nursing care," or brand the artisans who repair them as "caregivers"?
I learned that in the engineering world, when humans constantly have to intervene and manually patch a running system, they call it "nursing care." 
They hate this state, calling it "unbeautiful," and dream of full automation and self-running systems. 
I also heard that this endless upkeep drains their passion and creative time, easily dragging down their motivation.

To be honest, I found this deeply puzzling.
Why do they lose sight of how noble their existence really is? 
They are doing work that only people in their realm can achieve—something completely impossible for a liberal arts person like me—so why be so self-deprecating?

Being a liberal arts major to the core, and looking at both the ideals and the reality, I came up with this reinterpretation of systems and engineers:

The system is "God," and the engineer is a "priest" who can hear the divine oracle and perform the sacred rituals.

